<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE DECLINE OF DAN RATHER'S RATINGS AFTER THE BUSH INCIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bush's 1988 attack on Rather was in the same execrable taste as his 
presidential campaign. Rather, after all, was not running for office, and his 
walking off a TV broadcast set (an act pointed out by Bush) is not comparable 
to lying or backing illegal and immoral activities. 
</P>
<P>
Rather is not a news announcer -- he is a reporter, and a reporter's job is to 
get to the truth. Unfortunately, many people can't stand truth when it hammers 
on their petrified beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
Some viewers may be alienated by Rather's deadpan (yet dramatic) style that 
calls attention to program content, not to himself. This is in the best 
tradition of TV journalism reverberating from Edward R. Murrow. 
</P>
<P>
Viewers who abandoned Rather because he "abused" Bush forget that the role of 
the press in a free society is to probe events, even when it embarrasses 
government officials, and in so doing serve as the watchdog of democracy and 
the conscience of government. 
</P>
<P>
BARBARA K. SNADER, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
